snippet.textDisplay:
The Coke studio version of the "Rangabati Song" has touched millions of hearts across the globe. It gives us immense pride to see an Odiya song being accepted and enjoyed by people beyond religious & regional barricades. 
Now this is shocking that a faction of people belonging to Sambalpur, Odisha feel that their song has been stolen and wrongly staged without their permission. 
This is sad and exasperating to see that such vested interest groups who claim the ownership of the song have long forgotten to take this legendary song to an international podium, when they really could have and they remained satisfied with the then felicitations. Now when Sona Mahapatra(with her team) and Rituraj Mohanty took this song to such a level that for the first time this regional song derived huge global appreciation on an open international platform, the other faction here seeks legal processes to sue these young talents. This is very annoying and to that misguided faction I would say that you people have ignored the universal law of "Perform or Perish". You didn't perform then, so now when somebody else does it so well, keep your ego aside and appreciate their effort in taking your legacy to the modern aura. They have derived from you and they have redefined your creation, and in return they only brought more appreciation for your song. Instead of suing, bless them !!!

snippet.textDisplay:
The comments on this video are representative of the rut we Odias are in and why we would continue to stay there. We are a resource-rich yet financially poor state, we lag behind on almost all parameters, most people in the country aren't even aware about Odisha and Odias, the no. of Odia celebrities in the national consciousness can be counted on one hand. Even many Odias feel ashamed to disclose their Odia roots to outsiders.
Yet, instead of applauding the efforts made by Sona Mohapatra and team, we are busy criticising them. I agree that the original had a distinctive delightful Sambalpuri flavour, but this is not that song. Popular culture has proven time and again that a remake is never as good as the original, a few exceptions notwithstanding. If we need people to recognise and respect our culture, we need to make them aware of it. This is exactly what the team here has done.
I have always believed that we Odias are not good at marketing our skills and that's why we are not able to appreciate a fine example of marketing, which this video is. If we remove our rose-tinted glasses and judge this song without the burden of nostalgia, we would realise that this is a well-enacted song and peppy enough to generate eyeballs and curiosity towards our culture. Popular culture is extremely important in shaping opinions and we need more such efforts to gain a place in the national consciousness.
